## 4. Important Things to Know

### **The "Sign in with Apple" Requirement is Make-or-Break**

This is the **#1 rejection reason** for apps using third-party logins:
- If your app offers Microsoft, Google, Facebook, or any third-party login, Apple **requires** "Sign in with Apple" as an equally prominent option
- It must be the same size button, in the same location
- This is **non-negotiable**—Apple enforces this strictly
- **Why?** Apple wants users to have a privacy-focused option that doesn't share data with third parties

### **Two Different Stores, Two Different Personalities**

**Apple App Store:**
- **Strict gatekeeper**: Human reviewers manually test every app
- **Expensive**: $149/year ongoing cost
- **Fast reviews**: Usually 24-48 hours
- **Higher standards**: Expects polished, native apps (not just websites wrapped as apps)
- **Can appeal**: Detailed feedback, can dispute decisions

**Google Play Store:**
- **More relaxed**: Mix of automated and human review
- **Cheap**: $25 one-time fee (pay once, done forever)
- **Slower initial review**: 3-7 days for first submission
- **Flexible testing**: Multiple testing phases (Internal → Closed → Open → Production)
- **Detailed disclosures**: Data Safety form is very comprehensive

### **AI Disclosure is Mandatory (New in 2025)**

Both stores now strictly enforce AI transparency:
- Must clearly label when responses are AI-generated
- Can't pretend AI responses are human expert advice
- Must include disclaimers: "Walter is an AI assistant. Quotes are indicative only and not professional financial advice. Verify with a licensed broker."
- Must moderate for harmful content

### **Privacy is the Top Priority**

Both stores treat privacy as the most important factor:
- **Privacy policy must be public** (not behind a login)
- **Must accurately declare all data collection** (if you collect emails but don't declare it, instant rejection)
- **Must explain WHY you collect data**, not just what
- **Must offer data deletion** (users can request removal)
- **Microphone access requires clear explanation** (popup text explaining why you need the microphone)

### **Testing is Essential Before Submission**

Before submitting:
- Test on **real devices**, not just simulators
- Test on **multiple screen sizes** (small phones, large phones, tablets)
- Test **edge cases**: No internet, denied microphone permission, expired login
- Have **non-technical people test** (if your mom can't figure it out, reviewers will reject it)
- Ensure **zero crashes** (even one crash during review = automatic rejection)

### **Demo Accounts Save Time**

Both stores require test credentials if login is needed:
- Create a dedicated `reviewer@waltervoice.com` account
- Pre-populate with sample data (fake quotes, chat history)
- Include credentials in "Review Notes"
- Don't delete or change during review (reviewers get locked out = rejection)
- Keep active after approval (needed for future update reviews)

### **Timeline Reality Check**

The document estimates **6-10 weeks total**, but assumes:
- You already have a finished, tested app
- All legal documents ready
- Business verification documents prepared
- Nothing goes wrong

**Reality:**
- First submissions almost always get rejected at least once (add 3-7 days)
- D-U-N-S number can take full 10 business days
- If you're new to app development, add 2-4 weeks for learning curve
- Each reviewer question adds 1-3 days

### **Hidden Costs Beyond Registration Fees**

Document lists $149 AUD + $25 USD, but hidden costs include:
- **Designer**: Professional screenshots, icons, graphics ($200-$1000 or DIY)
- **Legal review**: Lawyer reviewing privacy policy ($500-$2000)
- **Testing devices**: Various iPhones and Android phones (borrow or buy used)
- **EAS Build**: Expo's cloud service has usage limits (may need paid tier)
- **Optional**: App preview videos, professional copywriting ($300-$1500)

### **The PWA Workaround**

Progressive Web Apps (PWA) can bypass stores:
- Users install directly from your website
- **Pros**: No approval, no fees, instant updates, works on both platforms
- **Cons**: Not searchable in stores, less trusted, can't access all phone features, harder to monetize

Good interim solution while waiting for approval.

### **Review is a Dialogue, Not a Pass/Fail Test**

Don't fear rejection:
- **Rejections include specific feedback**: "Add Sign in with Apple," "Privacy policy link broken"
- **You can fix and resubmit**: Review restarts within 24 hours
- **You can appeal**: Both stores have appeal processes
- **Reviewers want you to succeed**: They enforce policies to protect users, not block apps arbitrarily

### **Accessibility is Required**

WCAG 2.1 AA standards ensure people with disabilities can use the app:
- Screen reader support
- Sufficient color contrast
- Keyboard navigation
- Audio captions
- Both stores check this, and it's legally required in Australia

